Everybody in Europe wore them at some point, even Germans, French, everyone but they gradually removed them. It was part of modesty of a woman in Christianity but as people become less and less religious (which is very bad) they are removing these headscarfs and they are starting to show more and more skin, shorter dresses and so on which again is very BAD in my view. What?!? I am so shocked. A country girl ashamed to be known as a country yokel? Don't worry, I get you. That beautiful land produced a beautifully sweet girl. I was born in a very small town in Indiana USA. Small towns linked together by roads. I never hid the fact of my background. I think I understood young that variety is the spice of life. We all dreamed of the day we would leave home. We coined a very prophetic phrase, " in a town this small every road leads out of town". But later in life most of us dream of going back eventually. If you want an idea of my first 18 years watch the original Footloose movie with Kevin Bacon. Take stock of the people and the town. It all looks very familiar to me. Makes me sentimental. I loved travelling, thank you for this video.

The concept of "sarmale" was brought to this part of the world during the Ottoman Empire occupation and that's why they are quite popular (in some way or another) all over E-Europe. The traditional romanian stuffing for sarmale is rice, diced onions and minced pork. However, in the south of Romania we also make them with grape leaves, stuff them with minced poultry and boil them in white wine (at least that's how my mother makes them). The ones you cooked in this video are "sarmale de post" meaning without meat, vegetarian.

What you do is you chop up the grape leaves, and put them into the stuffing, and wrap them in the cabbage leaf.  My Ukrainian grandma used cabbage leafs, and my Georgian grandma used grape leaves.  I fused the two together.  I like the substantial texture of the cabbage, and the earthy flavor that the grape leaf adds.  So I get to have both!  You can buy the grape leaves in a can, or a jar.

I, too, was born in a small town. My town is Stetson, Maine, USA. My Dad built our 2 story cabin. We had a well with a hand pump, to pump the water up out of the ground and we would heat it on the stove for everything that needed hot water. There were always salamanders hiding in the well. We had a shed for a workshop and the cow, pony, pig, and 2 goats also had a larger shed to live in. We cooked on an iron stove powered by wood. I miss toasting bread on that stove. The toast came off the top of that stove browned, but soft and it was so tasty that it didn't even need butter. This stove is also how we heated the place. We had an outhouse, outside of course, instead of a working toilet inside. We lived on a dirt road. We were poor, but we didn't realize it at the time. We were happier then than we are now.

After leaving home I lived in London for a year and to be honest I realized it wasn't for me. Anyway, to cut a long story short, I have lived and worked abroad a lot and the last project I did was in Slovakia, in the Orava region which borders Poland. Slovakia and Poland are quite different, I would say Slovakia still has a real peasant mentality, and the food in general is not good, it is just stodge and not a lot of flavour. I was there for almost 5 years. Village life in east Europe is very insular, if you didn't grow up with them they will not be willing to make friends. Sure they are polite and will chat, but that is about the limit.

I came back to the UK last year and once again in London and I love it. I hadn't realized how much I miss the energy and action of a city where things happen and there is always something to see. And you will be surprised how easy it can be to talk to strangers and neighbours in London. It has really surprised me.
You should visit Romania then ! People here will love to be friends with you! And the food is soo good 😌
